United States changes visa allocation rules
People will have to turn to the Visa Service Centres before they interview the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
Since 10 January 2011, the process of negotiating visas for the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to turn to the Centres of the Visa Application Service (shortening from the English language ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
Staff from ASC will receive biometric information from the applicant and will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of issuing a visa will be lower, no longer necessary to pay the meeting fee, the second to process the application and the other to deliver the transport service document.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for a business and investor visa.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular official, but only turn to the nearest ASC where they submit their documents and get their fingerprints.
Given that biometric information will be collected in ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee of $26.
For further information on the new procedure, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolethines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
